"1070–Male":"1070–Deceased","1085–1143":"1085–1143","1016–1081":"1016–1081","0992–1034":"0992–1034","1091":"1091","1143":"1143","1033":"1033","1085":"1085","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","Abt 1030":"about 1030","1016":"1016","1115":"1115","0992":"0992","1034":"1034","Abt 1060":"about 1060","8 December 1091":"8 December 1091","Castle Ivry, Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","France":"France","Beaufour, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Beaufour, Calvados, Normandy, France","Lowdham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaufou","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name in the case of the   Domesday Book   tenants from Beaufour (Calvados), which is recorded as  <i>Belfou</i>,  <i>Beaufou</i> in 1100 and as  <i>Bellefai</i> in about 1160 (   Tengvik  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Boffee","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["English: locative name from either of two places in Lancs, namely Bispham near Blackpool ( <i>Bischopham</i>, 1086 in   Domesday Book  ) or Bispham in Croston."]},{"name":"Buffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffy","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Tengvik","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name in the case of the   Domesday Book   tenants from Beaufour (Calvados), which is recorded as  <i>Belfou</i>,  <i>Beaufou</i> in 1100 and as  <i>Bellefai</i> in about 1160 (   Tengvik  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Beaufou was born about 1030, his father, Richard de Beaufour, was 15 and his mother, Emma d’Ivry et de Bayeux, was 40. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with unknown. He died on 8 December 1091, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"Abt 1030–8 December 1091":"umbes 1030–8. detsember 1091","1030–1091":"1030–1091","1033–1115":"1033–1115","–Female":"Surnud","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1085–1143":"1085–1143","1016–1081":"1016–1081","0992–1034":"0992–1034","1091